'''6G''' is the proposed and upcoming sixth generation of the [[cellular network|mobile communications]] technology and the planned successor to [[5G]] (ITU-R [[IMT-2020]]). As of 2026, development is coordinated by the [[International Telecommunication Union]] (ITU-R) within its IMT-2030 framework, defined in Recommendation ITU-R M.2160-0.<ref>{{cite web |title=Recommendation ITU-R M.2160-0 |url=https://www.itu.int/en/ITU-R/study-groups/rsg5/rwp5d/imt-2030/Pages/default.aspx |website=ITU – International Telecommunication Union |date=November 2023 |access-date=April 3, 2024}}</ref>

ITU-R oversees related work by [[3GPP]] and [[ETSI]], together with the [[Next Generation Mobile Networks]] (NGMN) Alliance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Introduction to 3GPP Release 19 and 6G planning |url=https://www.3gpp.org/news-events/partner-news/atis-webinar-rel19 |website=3GPP |date=2024 |access-date=April 3, 2024}}</ref> 3GPP is finalizing Release 18 for 5G Advanced and preparing Release 19 for early 6G research.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Lin |first=Xingqin |date=September 2022 |title=An overview of 5G Advanced evolution in 3GPP Release 18 |journal=IEEE Communications Standards Magazine |volume=6 |issue=3 |pages=77–83 |doi=10.1109/MCOMSTD.0001.2200001 |bibcode=2022ICStM...6c..77L }}</ref> IMT-2030 defines performance targets for future mobile systems and tracks 6G standardization.<ref>{{cite web |title=IMT towards 2030 and beyond |url=https://www.itu.int/en/ITU-R/study-groups/rsg5/rwp5d/imt-2030/Pages/default.aspx |website=ITU – International Telecommunication Union |date=November 2023 |access-date=April 3, 2024}}</ref>

Research and testing are in progress at major equipment vendors, operators, and institutes. Companies including [[Ericsson]], [[Nokia]], [[Huawei]], [[Samsung]], [[LG]], [[Apple Inc.|Apple]], [[NTT Docomo]], [[Bharti Airtel|Airtel]], and [[Jio]] have announced 6G programs.<ref>{{cite web |title=Airtel, Vi push for work on 6G tech |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/telecom/telecom-news/airtel-vi-push-for-work-on-6g-tech/articleshow/88626707.cms |website=The Economic Times |date=January 2022 |access-date=October 20, 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Indian Telecom Jio partners with University of Oulu over 6G development |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/technology/tech-news-technology/the-university-of-oulu-announces-its-6g-collaboration-with-jio-to-explore-digital-opportunities-7733762/ |website=The Indian Express |date=January 2022 |access-date=August 5, 2022}}</ref> Governments in North America, Europe, and Asia are funding national 6G initiatives through the [[European Union|EU]], the United States, China, India, Japan, and South Korea.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-08-22 |title=India’s 6G Vision: Pioneering Next-Generation Connectivity - OpenGov Asia |url=https://opengovasia.com/indias-6g-vision-pioneering-next-generation-connectivity/ |access-date=2026-05-20 |website=opengovasia.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=China starts development of 6G after launching 5G networks |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/11/07/china-starts-6g-development-having-just-turned-on-its-5g-mobile-network.html |website=CNBC |date=November 2019 |access-date=July 30, 2020}}</ref>

6G aims to achieve higher data rates, lower [[Latency (engineering)|latency]], and greater [[Efficient energy use|energy efficiency]] than 5G.<ref>{{cite web |last=Fisher |first=Tim |title=6G: What it is and when to expect it |url=https://www.lifewire.com/6g-wireless-4685524 |website=Lifewire |date=April 2022 |access-date=April 3, 2024}}</ref> Planned advances include new [[air interface]] designs, improved coding and modulation, and reconfigurable intelligent surfaces.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Björnson |first1=Emil |last2=Özdogan |first2=Özgecan |last3=Larsson |first3=Erik G. |date=December 2020 |title=Reconfigurable intelligent surfaces: three myths and two critical questions |journal=IEEE Communications Magazine |volume=58 |issue=12 |pages=90–96 |doi=10.1109/MCOM.001.2000407|arxiv=2006.03377 |bibcode=2020IComM..58l..90B }}</ref> Research also explores integration with satellite, Wi-Fi, and non-terrestrial networks, as well as distributed [[edge computing]] for [[augmented reality|AR]], [[virtual reality|VR]], and [[artificial intelligence|AI]] applications.<ref name=NGMN2023>{{cite web |title=NGMN 6G position statement |url=https://www.ngmn.org/wp-content/uploads/NGMN_6G_Position_Statement.pdf |website=NGMN Alliance |date=November 2023 |access-date=April 3, 2024}}</ref>

[[Machine learning]] and AI are expected to help manage networks, allocate spectrum, and optimize services.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Saad |first=W. |title=A vision of 6G wireless systems: applications, trends, technologies, and open research problems |journal=IEEE Network |volume=34 |issue=3 |pages=134–142 |year=2020 |doi=10.1109/MNET.001.1900287 |bibcode=2020IEEEN..34c.134S }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Yang |first=H. |title=Artificial-intelligence-enabled 6G networks |journal=IEEE Network |volume=34 |issue=6 |pages=272–280 |year=2020 |doi=10.1109/MNET.011.2000195|arxiv=1912.05744 }}</ref>

According to the NGMN Alliance, 6G development should focus on demonstrable user needs and avoid unnecessary replacement of existing 5G [[radio access network]] equipment.<ref name=NGMN2023 /> Analysts note that 5G revenue growth has been slower than predicted, leading to a cautious approach to 6G investment.<ref>{{cite web |last=Meyer |first=Dan |title=When will the 5G RAN market slump end? |url=https://www.sdxcentral.com/articles/news/when-will-the-5g-ran-market-slump-end/2023/11/ |website=SDX Central |date=November 2023 |access-date=April 3, 2024}}</ref> Commercial deployment of 6G is anticipated in the early 2030s, following standardization milestones later in the 2020s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Korea plans to launch 6G service in 2028 |url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2023/08/113_345765.html |website=The Korea Times |date=February 2023 |access-date=August 31, 2023}}</ref>

== Expectations ==
{{Update|section|date=April 2024}}
6G networks are expected to be developed and released by the early 2030s.<ref>{{Cite news|title=China sends world's first 6G test satellite into orbit|language=en-GB|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-asia-china-54852131|access-date=November 7, 2020|archive-date=November 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108080701/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-asia-china-54852131|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=November 6, 2020|title=China launches 'world's first 6G experiment satellite'|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/china-launches-worlds-first-6g-experiment-satellite/2034321|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201106101300/https://www.aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/china-launches-worlds-first-6g-experiment-satellite/2034321 |archive-date=November 6, 2020 |access-date=November 7, 2020|website=Anadolu Agency}}</ref> The largest number of 6G patents have been filed in China.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Asghar |first1=Muhammad Zeeshan |last2=Memon |first2=Shafique Ahmed |last3=Hämäläinen |first3=Jyri |date=May 23, 2022 |title=Evolution of Wireless Communication to 6G: Potential Applications and Research Directions |journal=[[Sustainability (journal)|Sustainability]] |language=en |volume=14 |issue=10 |page=6356 |doi=10.3390/su14106356 |issn=2071-1050 |doi-access=free|bibcode=2022Sust...14.6356A }}</ref>

=== Features ===
Academic publications since the early 2020s have been conceptualizing 6G and new features that may be included. Artificial intelligence (AI) is included in many predictions, from 6G supporting AI infrastructure to "AI designing and optimizing 6G architectures, protocols, and operations."<ref>{{cite magazine | last1 = Letaief | first1 = Khaled B. | last2 = Chen | first2 = Wei | last3 = Shi | first3 = Yuanming | last4 = Zhang | first4 = Jun | last5 = Zhang | first5 = Ying-Jun Angela | author5-link = Ying Jun Zhang | arxiv = 1904.11686 | date = August 2019 | doi = 10.1109/mcom.2019.1900271 | issue = 8 | magazine = IEEE Communications Magazine | pages = 84–90 | title = The roadmap to 6G: AI empowered wireless networks | volume = 57}}</ref> Another study in [[Nature (journal)|''Nature Electronics'']] looks to provide a framework for 6G research, stating, "We suggest that human-centric mobile communications will still be the most important application of 6G and the 6G network should be human-centric. Thus, high security, secrecy and privacy should be key features of 6G and should be given particular attention by the wireless research community."<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Dang|first1=Shuping|last2=Amin|first2=Osama|last3=Shihada|first3=Basem|last4=Alouini|first4=Mohamed-Slim|date=January 2020|title=What should 6G be?|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41928-019-0355-6|journal=Nature Electronics|language=en|volume=3|issue=1|pages=20–29|doi=10.1038/s41928-019-0355-6|issn=2520-1131|arxiv=1906.00741|s2cid=211095143|access-date=April 28, 2021|archive-date=January 21, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220121113816/https://www.nature.com/articles/s41928-019-0355-6|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Transmission ===
The frequency bands for 6G are undetermined. Initially, [[Terahertz radiation|Terahertz]] was considered an important band for 6G, as indicated by the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]], which stated that "Frequencies from 100&nbsp;GHz to 3&nbsp;THz are promising bands for the next generation of wireless communication systems because of the wide swaths of unused and unexplored [[Electromagnetic spectrum|spectrum]]."<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Rappaport|first1=Theodore S.|last2=Xing|first2=Yunchou|last3=Kanhere|first3=Ojas|last4=Ju|first4=Shihao|last5=Madanayake|first5=Arjuna|last6=Mandal|first6=Soumyajit|last7=Alkhateeb|first7=Ahmed|last8=Trichopoulos|first8=Georgios C.|date=2019|title=Wireless Communications and Applications Above 100 GHz: Opportunities and Challenges for 6G and Beyond|journal=IEEE Access|volume=7|pages=78729–78757|doi=10.1109/ACCESS.2019.2921522|bibcode=2019IEEEA...778729R |issn=2169-3536|doi-access=free}}</ref>

One of the challenges in supporting the required high transmission speeds will be the limitation of energy consumption and associated thermal protection in the electronic circuits.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Smulders |first=Peter |year=2013 |title=The Road to 100 Gb/s Wireless and Beyond: Basic Issues and Key Directions |journal=IEEE Communications Magazine |volume=51 |issue=12 |pages=86–91 |doi=10.1109/MCOM.2013.6685762 |bibcode=2013IComM..51l..86S |s2cid=12358456}}</ref>

As of now, mid bands are being considered by WRC for 6G/IMT-2030.

=== Coverage ===
In June 2021, according to Samsung's white paper, using Sub-THz 6G spectrum, their indoor data rate was successful for 6 Gbit/s at 15 meters distance. The following year, Samsung reported 12 Gbit/s at 30 meters distance and 2.3 Gbit/s at 120 meters distance.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-05-08 |title=Samsung Unveils 6G Spectrum White Paper and 6G Research Findings |url=https://news.samsung.com/global/samsung-unveils-6g-spectrum-white-paper-and-6g-research-findings |url-status=live |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20250722102922/https://news.samsung.com/global/samsung-unveils-6g-spectrum-white-paper-and-6g-research-findings |archive-date= 2025-07-22|access-date=2025-05-10 |website=[[Samsung]]}}</ref>

In September 2023, LG successfully tested 6 Gbit/s transmission and reception at 500 meters distance outdoor.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-09-26 |title=LG Sets New Record, Successfully Transmitting, Receiving 6G THz Data Over Distance of 500 Meters |url=https://www.lg.com/global/newsroom/news/corporate/lg-sets-new-record-successfully-transmitting-receiving-6g-thz-data-over-distance-of-500-meters/ |url-status=live |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20260504231946/https://www.lg.com/global/newsroom/news/corporate/lg-sets-new-record-successfully-transmitting-receiving-6g-thz-data-over-distance-of-500-meters/ |archive-date= 2026-05-04|access-date=2025-05-10 |website=[[LG]] |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Warwick |first=Stephen |date=2023-09-26 |title=The biggest 6G test yet just took place, bringing commercial use 'one step closer' |url=https://www.imore.com/phones/the-biggest-6g-test-yet-just-took-place-bringing-commercial-use-one-step-closer |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250510160922/https://www.imore.com/phones/the-biggest-6g-test-yet-just-took-place-bringing-commercial-use-one-step-closer |archive-date=2025-05-10 |access-date=2025-05-10 |website=iMore |language=en}}</ref>

== Terahertz and millimeter-wave research ==

Research into terahertz radiation (300–3,000 GHz) and [[millimeter-wave]] frequencies (30–300 GHz) explores their potential for 6G mobile networks. These high frequencies can support large data rates but are easily blocked by obstacles. Unlike the [[microwave]] bands (2–30 GHz) used in [[5G]] and [[Wi-Fi]], and the lower-frequency [[radio waves]] used in 1G–4G, their commercial feasibility remains uncertain, as 5G millimeter-wave use is limited by cost.

=== Industry initiatives ===
In 2020, the [[Alliance for Telecommunications Industry Solutions]] (ATIS) launched the Next G Alliance, a group including [[AT&T]], Ericsson, [[Telus Communications|Telus]], [[Verizon]], [[T-Mobile US|T-Mobile]], [[Microsoft]], and Samsung. The alliance aims to advance North American 6G research.<ref name="ATIS">{{cite web |title=ATIS Launches Next G Alliance to Advance North American Leadership in 6G |url=https://www.atis.org/press-releases/atis-launches-next-g-alliance-to-advance-north-american-leadership-in-6g/ |first=Marcella |last=Wolfe |date=October 13, 2020 |access-date=February 18, 2021 |publisher=Alliance for Telecommunications Industry Solutions |language=en |archive-date=February 22, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210222105109/https://www.atis.org/press-releases/atis-launches-next-g-alliance-to-advance-north-american-leadership-in-6g/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Experimental studies ===
In 2022, researchers from Purple Mountain Laboratories, a state-affiliated institute in Nanjing, China, reported a 206.25 Gbit/s data rate in laboratory tests using the terahertz band. The team said the results may support future 6G research.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scmp.com/tech/big-tech/article/3162411/chinese-lab-says-it-made-breakthrough-6g-mobile-technology-global |title=Chinese lab says it made a breakthrough in 6G mobile technology as global standards-setting race heats up |last=Pan |first=Che |work=South China Morning Post |date=January 6, 2022 |access-date=June 26, 2024 |language=en }}</ref>

Also in 2022, another Chinese research group reported a data transmission rate of 1 Tbit/s over 1 km using [[optical vortex|vortex millimeter-wave]] transmission, a technique that uses radio waves shaped to spiral as they travel. The work built on earlier European studies from the 1990s. Vortex waves weaken as they expand with distance. The researchers used a custom transmitter and receiver to focus and decode multiple rotating wave modes.<ref>{{cite web |last=Chen |first=Stephen |date=February 10, 2022 |title=Race to 6G: Chinese researchers declare data streaming record with whirling radio waves |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3166372/race-6g-chinese-researchers-declare-data-streaming-record |url-access=subscription |website=South China Morning Post |access-date=May 16, 2023 |archive-date=May 10, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230510042740/https://www.scmp.com/news/china/science/article/3166372/race-6g-chinese-researchers-declare-data-streaming-record |language=en |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2023, [[Nagoya University]] in Japan created three-dimensional [[waveguide]] structures made of superconducting [[niobium]] for communication in the 100 GHz range. The superconducting design reduced signal loss from absorption and radiation and was proposed for high-frequency 6G transmission.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techxplore.com/news/2023-10-superconducting-niobium-waveguide-high-precision-communications.html |title=Superconducting niobium waveguide achieves high-precision communications for B5G/6G networks |author=Nagoya University |website=Tech Xplore |date=October 5, 2023 |access-date=October 7, 2023 |archive-date=October 5, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231005145246/https://techxplore.com/news/2023-10-superconducting-niobium-waveguide-high-precision-communications.html |language=en |url-status=live }}</ref>

Research on terahertz and millimeter-wave communication continues worldwide as part of global efforts to develop future wireless standards.

== Experimental satellites ==

In November 2020, China launched a [[Long March 6]] vehicle that carried a satellite testing components for potential 6G communication. Chinese state media described it as "the world's first 6G satellite", a claim not independently verified. The mission studied terahertz-band transmission and other 6G-related technologies.<ref>{{cite news |title=China sends 'world's first 6G' test satellite into orbit |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-asia-china-54852131 |agency=BBC |access-date=November 7, 2020 |archive-date=November 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201108080701/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-asia-china-54852131 |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Geopolitics ==

Geopolitical competition during the rollout of 5G has continued to shape the development of 6G. During that time, China reduced participation by foreign vendors and relied more on domestic suppliers such as [[Huawei]] and [[ZTE]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Morris |first=I. |title=Ericsson and Nokia are nearer to the endgame in China |website=Light Reading |date=October 24, 2022 |url=https://www.lightreading.com/5g/ericsson-and-nokia-are-nearer-to-the-endgame-in-china |access-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106162004/https://www.lightreading.com/5g/ericsson-and-nokia-are-nearer-to-the-endgame-in-china |language=en }}</ref>{{Failed verification|sources stated Ericsson "was punished for [Swedish] government's decision to ban Huawei and ZTE"|date=February 2024}}  
Several Western countries later restricted Huawei and ZTE after government investigations accused Chinese firms of cyber-espionage and [[Allegations of intellectual property infringement by China|intellectual-property theft]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Zhong |first=R. |title='Prospective Threat' of Chinese Spying Justifies Huawei Ban, U.S. Says |work=The New York Times |date=July 5, 2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/05/technology/huawei-lawsuit-us-government.html |access-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106162418/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/05/technology/huawei-lawsuit-us-government.html |language=en }}</ref>
These developments affected early 6G planning and global supply chains.

Analysts have suggested that such divisions could lead to a split in 6G standards.<ref>{{cite web |last=Dano |first=M. |title=6G fragmentation may have just gotten a little closer |website=Light Reading |date=October 5, 2023 |url=https://www.lightreading.com/6g/6g-fragmentation-may-have-just-gotten-a-little-closer |access-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106161853/https://www.lightreading.com/6g/6g-fragmentation-may-have-just-gotten-a-little-closer |language=en }}</ref> Analysts also expect competition in international standards bodies to grow.<ref>{{cite journal |title=6G Is Years Away, but the Power Struggles Have Already Begun |journal=IEEE Spectrum |publisher=Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers |date=November 29, 2021 |url=https://spectrum.ieee.org/6g-geopolitics |access-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106164043/https://spectrum.ieee.org/6g-geopolitics |language=en }}</ref>

A joint statement issued in February 2024 by the United States, Australia, Canada, Czech Republic, Finland, France, Japan, South Korea, Sweden, and the United Kingdom endorsed shared 6G principles for open, global, and secure connectivity.<ref>{{cite web |last=Habeshian |first=S. |date=February 26, 2024 |title=U.S. and allies endorse 6G principles amid tech race with China |website=Axios |publisher=Axios Media |url=https://www.axios.com/2024/02/27/6g-wireless-us-allies-principles-china-race |access-date=February 28, 2024 |archive-date=February 27, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240227213741/https://www.axios.com/2024/02/27/6g-wireless-us-allies-principles-china-race |language=en }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |date=February 27, 2024 |title=Joint Statement Endorsing Principles for 6G: Secure, Open, and Resilient by Design |publisher=The White House |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2024/02/26/joint-statement-endorsing-principles-for-6g-secure-open-and-resilient-by-design/ |access-date=February 28, 2024 |archive-date=February 28, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240228011157/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2024/02/26/joint-statement-endorsing-principles-for-6g-secure-open-and-resilient-by-design/ |language=en }}</ref>

Governments in several countries, including China and India, have made 6G a national priority. The technology appears in China's [[Fourteenth five-year plan (China)|Fourteenth Five-Year Plan]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Pettyjohn |first=S. |title=U.S.-China Competition and the Race to 6G |website=Center for a New American Security |date=November 14, 2023 |url=https://www.cnas.org/publications/commentary/u-s-china-competition-and-the-race-to-6g |access-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106161448/https://www.cnas.org/publications/commentary/u-s-china-competition-and-the-race-to-6g |language=en }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Translation: 14th Five-Year Plan for National Informatization – Dec. 2021 |website=DigiChina |publisher=Stanford University |date=January 24, 2022 |url=https://digichina.stanford.edu/work/translation-14th-five-year-plan-for-national-informatization-dec-2021/ |access-date=January 6, 2024 |archive-date=January 5, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240105230534/https://digichina.stanford.edu/work/translation-14th-five-year-plan-for-national-informatization-dec-2021/ |language=en }}</ref> India's 6G direction is defined by the Bharat 6G Vision document, published in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Government of India, "Bharat 6G Vision Document," Department of Telecommunications, March 2023. |url=https://bharat6galliance.com/bharat6G/}}</ref>

Governments have also promoted varied technology suppliers. Many support the [[Open RAN]] model, which lets hardware and software from different suppliers work together without vendor control.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kim |first1=M.-j. |last2=Eom |first2=D. |last3=Lee |first3=H. |title=The geopolitics of next generation mobile communication standardization: The case of open RAN |journal=Telecommunications Policy |publisher=Elsevier |volume=47 |issue=10 |year=2023 |article-number=102625 |doi=10.1016/j.telpol.2023.102625 |s2cid=265023622 |url=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.telpol.2023.102625 |language=en |url-access=subscription }}</ref>

Australia's telecommunications strategy includes early 6G planning. In March 2025, [[Telstra]] announced that 6G is expected in the 2030s, with $800&nbsp;million set aside to improve existing infrastructure over four years.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 9, 2025 |title=Australia's 5G network to get AI overhaul, as Telstra lays groundwork for 6G |website=9News Australia |publisher=Nine Entertainment |url=https://www.9news.com.au/national/telstra-ai-6g-australias-network-to-get-ai-overhaul-as-telstra-lays-groundwork/3c8c3723-9389-40c4-81e5-5a95a2023361 |access-date=March 12, 2025 |archive-date=March 12, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250312000000/https://www.9news.com.au/national/telstra-ai-6g-australias-network-to-get-ai-overhaul-as-telstra-lays-groundwork/3c8c3723-9389-40c4-81e5-5a95a2023361 |language=en }}</ref>

== Internet of Things ==
6G wireless communication networks are envisioned to revolutionize customer services and applications via the IoT (Internet of Things) toward a future of fully intelligent and autonomous systems. IoT connects sensor devices and networks to enable communication among people, physical objects, and equipment across a wide range of contexts.
